SIMPLE: lucid
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Lucid
<hw>Lu"cid</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L. <ets>lucidus</ets>,
fr. <ets>lux</ets>, <ets>lucis</ets>, light. See <er>Light</er>,
<pos>n.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Shining; bright; resplendent;
<as>as, the <ex>lucid</ex> orbs of heaven</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Lucid</qex>, like a glowworm.</q> <rj><qau>Sir I.
Newton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A court compact of <qex>lucid</qex> marbles.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Clear; transparent.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧ <xex>Lucid</xex>
streams.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Presenting a clear view; easily understood;
clear.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>lucid</qex> and interesting abstract of the debate.</q>
<rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Bright with the radiance of intellect; not darkened
or confused by delirium or madness; marked by the regular operations of
reason; <as>as, a <ex>lucid</ex> interval</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Luminous; bright; clear; transparent; sane;
reasonable. See <er>Luminous</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Lucidity</ent>⟦br⟧
